nodes.title: Model Script
widgets_values:
import torch
import torch.nn as nn
import math

class GeneratedModel(nn.Sequential):
    def __init__(self):
        # Initialize layers
        self.input_shape = [1, 28, 28]

        self.conv0 = nn.Conv2d(
            in_channels=1,
            out_channels=16,
            kernel_size=3,
            stride=1,
            padding=1,
            bias=True
        )

        self.norm1 = nn.BatchNorm2d(
            num_features=16,
            eps=1e-05,
            momentum=0.1,
            affine=True
        )

        self.pool3 = nn.MaxPool2d(
            kernel_size=2,
            stride=2,
            padding=0
        )

        self.conv4 = nn.Conv2d(
            in_channels=16,
            out_channels=8,
            kernel_size=3,
            stride=1,
            padding=1,
            bias=True
        )

        self.norm5 = nn.BatchNorm2d(
            num_features=8,
            eps=1e-05,
            momentum=0.1,
            affine=True
        )

        self.pool7 = nn.MaxPool2d(
            kernel_size=2,
            stride=2,
            padding=0
        )

        self.linear8 = nn.Linear(
            in_features=8,
            out_features=128,
            bias=True
        )
        self.activation8 = nn.ReLU()

        self.linear9 = nn.Linear(
            in_features=128,
            out_features=32,
            bias=True
        )

        self.linear10 = nn.Linear(
            in_features=32,
            out_features=128,
            bias=True
        )
        self.activation10 = nn.ReLU()

        self.linear11 = nn.Linear(
            in_features=128,
            out_features=392,
            bias=True
        )
        self.activation11 = nn.ReLU()

        class Reshape12(nn.Module):
            def __init__(self):
                super().__init__()
                self.target_shape = [8, 7, 7]

            def forward(self, x):
                batch_size = x.size(0)
                return x.view(batch_size, *self.target_shape)

        self.reshape12 = Reshape12()

        # Combine layers
        super().__init__(
            self.conv0,
            self.norm1,
            self.pool3,
            self.conv4,
            self.norm5,
            self.pool7,
            self.linear8,
            self.activation8,
            self.linear9,
            self.linear10,
            self.activation10,
            self.linear11,
            self.activation11,
            self.reshape12,
        )

nodes.title: Workflow Description
widgets_values:
This workflow implements an autoencoder neural network architecture for the FashionMNIST dataset that consists of:

Encoder Section:


Input layer accepting 28x28 grayscale fashion images
Two convolutional blocks with batch normalization and ReLU activation
MaxPooling layers for dimensionality reduction
Dense layers that compress the representation down to 32 dimensions (latent space)


Decoder Section:


Dense layers that expand from the 32-dimensional latent space
Reshape layer to prepare for deconvolution
Two transposed convolution blocks (deconvolution)
Final sigmoid activation to reconstruct the original image

The workflow demonstrates three key phases:

Training Phase:

Loads 10,000 training samples from FashionMNIST
Uses MSE loss and Adam optimizer
Trains for 200 epochs with early stopping
Includes comprehensive training metrics visualization

Testing Phase:

Evaluates the autoencoder on a separate test set
Visualizes reconstruction quality and metrics
Provides detailed analysis of model performance

Custom Image Inference:

Allows loading a custom clothing image ("hoodie.jpg")
Preprocesses the image to match FashionMNIST format (grayscale, 28x28)
Runs it through the trained autoencoder
Displays both the input and reconstructed images

The model achieves meaningful dimensionality reduction by compressing 784-dimensional images (28x28) down to 32 dimensions while maintaining the ability to reconstruct the essential features of the clothing items. The workflow includes extensive visualization and analysis tools to monitor training progress, evaluate reconstruction quality, and analyze the model's performance.
The final inference section is particularly interesting as it shows how the trained autoencoder can be applied to new, external images, demonstrating the model's generalization capabilities beyond the training dataset.
